NEW YORK (CBS.MW) -- U.S. stocks sloshed through a rather featureless
    session Friday as participants bided their time ahead of next week's crush of earnings
    releases. Few groups stood out in the lightly-attended session. Despite Friday's meek
    advances, traders like the fact that profit-taking has been scarce over the past few
    sessions following a heady six-day runup. Friday's activity featured the same behavior,
    with most of the current cycle's speculative growth stock leaders showing a dry-up in
    volume. All indications point to a bang-up second-quarter earnings season. The question in
    many minds is whether the market has already discounted the event in current prices. After
    all, the Nasdaq Composite has chalked up a tidy 15 percent gain in just the past four
    weeks.

Headlines.Author: CBS.MarketWatch.com
Headlines.Headline: Check Point likely to rise

#text:
Check
    Point Software

shares may get a boost Friday as the company said sales and earnings
    for the most-recent quarter more than doubled. The security software maker said it
    earned 37 cents per share on revenue of $30 million. That compares to earnings of 15 cents
    per share on $11.6 million last year. Analysts expected the Israeli company to earn 30
    cents per share. This marks the second-straight quarter Check Point has blown away
    analysts' projections. The strong results helped push shares above 50 in November,
    although they now trade about 30 percent lower.

Headlines.Author: Binti T. Harvey
Headlines.Headline: Gateway beats estimate by 15 cents

#text:
Shares of Gateway
    2000 Inc.

are poised to rise Friday after posting a strong fourth-quarter turnaround
    and beating expectations by 15 cents. Gateway earned 59 cents a share, crushing Wall
    Street's consensus expectation of 45 cents. A year ago, the mail-order PC manufacturer
    earned 56 cents. Revenue rose 28 percent to $1.98 billion vs. $1.55 billion the same
    period a year ago.Gateway shipped 850,000 units during the fourth quarter, a 38
    percent increase from a year earlier. Chairman and CEO Ted Waite said, "Our
    record quarter was the result of executing well on the basics of our direct business
    model:  forecasting, inventory management and cost controls." However,
    average unit prices decreased 4 percent to $2,326 from $2,430 in third quarter, and fell 8
    percent from the average price of $2,529 a year ago. Gateway said gross margins were 18
    percent, down from 19 percent a year earlier, but "somewhat better than
    expectations due to lower component costs." The stock closed up 1/4 at 34 ahead of
    the report.

Headlines.BodyHeadline: Gateway beats estimate by 15 cents

Headlines.Headline: Vanguard adds to index lineup

PARAGRAPH.#text:
The Vanguard Group has filed a
    registration statement with the U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission for three new
    index mutual funds. The proposed offerings will be added to Vanguard Index Trust family. Mid
    Capitalization Stock portfolio will be managed to parallel the investment performance
    of the Standard & Poor's MidCap 400 Index, a medium-sized companies benchmark. Small
    Capitalization Value Stock portfolio will track Standard & Poor's SmallCap
    600/BARRA Value Index, composed of stocks with higher-than-average dividend yields and
    lower-than-average price/earnings and price/book ratios. And Small Capitalization
    Growth Stock portfolio will follow Standard & Poor's SmallCap 600/BARRA Growth
    Index, including stocks with lower-than-average dividend yields and higher-than-average
    price/earnings and price/book ratios.

#text:

    Communications Corp.

chairman James Barksdale Thursday outlined a two-pronged
    plan to return his company to growth and profits. In a conference call with reporters, he
    announced one step is making available the company's suite of client software for

    build our other businesses to the point where we can make the product free," said Mike
